
[1]prophet

   PROPH'ET, n. [L. propheta.]

   1. One that foretells future events; a predicter; a foreteller.

   2. In Scripture, a person illuminated, inspired or instructed by God to
   announce future events; as Moses, Elijah, David, Isaiah, &c.

   3. An interpreter; one that explains or communicates sentiments. Ex.7.

   4. One who pretends to foretell; an imposter; as a false prophet. Acts
   13.

     of the prophets, among the Israelites, a school or college in which
      young men were educated and qualified for public teachers. These
                 students were called sons of the prophets.
